</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Radiation exposure from computed tomography (CT) has received much attention lately in the medical literature and the media, given the relatively high radiation dose that characterizes a CT examination. Although there are a variety of possible strategies for reducing radiation exposure from CT in an individual patient, optimal CT image acquisition requires that the radiologist understand new scanner technology and how to implement the most effective means of dose reduction while maintaining image quality. The authors describe a practical approach to dose reduction in cardiothoracic radiology, discussing CT radiation dose metrics (eg, CT dose index, dose-length product, effective diameter, and size-specific dose estimate) as well as CT scanner parameters that directly or indirectly influence radiation dose (eg, scan length, x-ray tube output, tube current modulation, pitch, image reconstruction techniques [including iterative reconstruction], and noise reduction). These variables are discussed in terms of their relative importance to image quality and the implications of parametric changes for image quality and diagnostic content, and practical recommendations are made for their immediate implementation in the clinical setting. Taken together, the principles of physics and key parameters involved in reducing radiation dose while maintaining image quality can serve as a “survival guide” for a diagnostic radiology practice.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.346140084">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.346140084">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig1.jpeg" height="1143" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Scanner report generated at the end of a CT pulmonary angiographic examination shows how the radiation dose can be estimated using the report. Note that the CTDI phantom must be 32 cm in diameter to represent the human body. The first row of the report is empty because the vast majority of currently used CT scanners do not generate radiation dose data for the scout view, although newly developed scanners provide the CTDI<sub>vol</sub> for the scout view as well. The corresponding DLP of the scout view is only about 2% of the DLP of the entire helical CT examination. The second row contains data from the axial scan performed for appropriate estimation of contrast enhancement (Smart Prep). Usually, 2–10 sections are acquired in axial mode at the same location (scan range = 0). The CTDI<sub>vol</sub> (13.16 mGy) is the sum of the CTDI<sub>vol</sub> values for all of the axial sections. Because the exact number of axial sections is known, the average CTDI<sub>vol</sub> for each section can be calculated (total CTDI<sub>vol</sub> divided by number of sections). The third row displays the actual scan range, CTDI<sub>vol</sub> (4.95 mGy), and DLP (4.95 mGy × length in centimeters, or 138 mGy-cm) for the diagnostic (helical) scan. The total DLP for the examination is the sum of the DLPs for the axial scan (6.57 mGy-cm) and diagnostic scan (138.04 mGy-cm), or 144.61 mGy-cm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig2.jpeg" height="791" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> CT image demonstrates how the scan length for pulmonary CT angiography, which focuses on the pulmonary arterial tree, usually extends from 2 cm above the aortic arch to the dome of the lower hemidiaphragm (average, 15 cm) (double-headed red arrow on right). This distance is substantially less than the average 25-cm coverage required for chest CT (double-headed red arrow on left). For the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism, a scan length of 10 cm can be used without loss of accuracy, although alternative diagnoses that could be seen at pulmonary CT angiography may be lost (<a href="#r25" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r25">25</a>). Scan length is selected on the basis of anatomic landmarks seen on the scout view.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig3a.jpeg" height="800" width="957" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> <b>(a)</b> Coronary CT angiographic image shows how coverage generally extends from the level of the carina to the inferior aspect of the heart on the anteroposterior scout view (red box). If a calcium score scan is performed prior to coronary CT angiography, the precise location of the coronary arteries can be determined, allowing further reduction of the scan length. <b>(b)</b> On average, the scan length for coronary CT angiography is 12–14 cm (red box). Precise selection of the z-axis coverage for cardiac CT angiography is made on the basis of anatomic landmarks.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig3b.jpeg" height="800" width="918" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> <b>(a)</b> Coronary CT angiographic image shows how coverage generally extends from the level of the carina to the inferior aspect of the heart on the anteroposterior scout view (red box). If a calcium score scan is performed prior to coronary CT angiography, the precise location of the coronary arteries can be determined, allowing further reduction of the scan length. <b>(b)</b> On average, the scan length for coronary CT angiography is 12–14 cm (red box). Precise selection of the z-axis coverage for cardiac CT angiography is made on the basis of anatomic landmarks.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig4a.jpeg" height="646" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> CT thoracic angiographic images obtained for assessment of the ascending aorta in a 45-year-old woman with chest pain show how a tube setting of 100 kVp <b>(a)</b> provides better aortic enhancement than does the more traditional 120-kVp tube setting <b>(b)</b>. Note that the higher noise level in <b>a</b> does not interfere with the diagnostic content of the image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig4b.jpeg" height="646" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> CT thoracic angiographic images obtained for assessment of the ascending aorta in a 45-year-old woman with chest pain show how a tube setting of 100 kVp <b>(a)</b> provides better aortic enhancement than does the more traditional 120-kVp tube setting <b>(b)</b>. Note that the higher noise level in <b>a</b> does not interfere with the diagnostic content of the image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig5a.jpeg" height="827" width="632" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> On retrospective 120-kVp <b>(a)</b> and 100-kVp <b>(b)</b> ECG-gated coronary CT angiographic images, the left anterior descending artery is diffusely affected by noncalcified plaque. The extent and severity of coronary atherosclerotic disease are depicted with equal precision on the two images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig5b.jpeg" height="827" width="593" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> On retrospective 120-kVp <b>(a)</b> and 100-kVp <b>(b)</b> ECG-gated coronary CT angiographic images, the left anterior descending artery is diffusely affected by noncalcified plaque. The extent and severity of coronary atherosclerotic disease are depicted with equal precision on the two images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig6a.jpeg" height="632" width="828" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> CT pulmonary angiographic images obtained at 90 mAs <b>(a)</b> and 10 mAs <b>(b)</b> (both images obtained at 100 kVp) show how substantially decreasing the tube current while leaving the peak voltage unchanged will still yield diagnostic images that allow the diagnosis of segmental artery pulmonary embolism (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig6b.jpeg" height="632" width="847" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> CT pulmonary angiographic images obtained at 90 mAs <b>(a)</b> and 10 mAs <b>(b)</b> (both images obtained at 100 kVp) show how substantially decreasing the tube current while leaving the peak voltage unchanged will still yield diagnostic images that allow the diagnosis of segmental artery pulmonary embolism (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig7a.jpeg" height="734" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Serial chest CT images obtained at 100 mAs <b>(a)</b> and 40 mAs <b>(b)</b> for follow-up of a pulmonary nodule show comparable diagnostic quality in assessing the lung parenchyma and airways.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig7b.jpeg" height="734" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Serial chest CT images obtained at 100 mAs <b>(a)</b> and 40 mAs <b>(b)</b> for follow-up of a pulmonary nodule show comparable diagnostic quality in assessing the lung parenchyma and airways.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig8a.jpeg" height="700" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> High-resolution chest CT images obtained during end inspiration at 100 mAs <b>(a)</b> and end expiration at 40 mAs <b>(b)</b> clearly depict a pulmonary nodule and air trapping.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig8b.jpeg" height="700" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> High-resolution chest CT images obtained during end inspiration at 100 mAs <b>(a)</b> and end expiration at 40 mAs <b>(b)</b> clearly depict a pulmonary nodule and air trapping.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig9.jpeg" height="1105" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Graph superimposed on a lateral scout view demonstrates the effect of longitudinal modulation, with variations of the tube current along the z-axis of the patient’s body. Tube current along the z-axis is determined on the basis of the CT scout view and a vendor-specific algorithm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig10.jpeg" height="341" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Graph superimposed on a lateral scout view shows tube current modulation in all three axes, with higher current at lateral imaging and lower current at anteroposterior imaging. (Courtesy of C. Suess, Siemens Healthcare.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig11.jpeg" height="1306" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> Graph and CT scan demonstrate how organ-specific tube modulation is designed to decrease radiation to dose-sensitive organs such as the breast. The fanlike area shown in blue denotes the area receiving substantially reduced current within the gantry, thus decreasing radiation to that particular body part.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig12a.jpeg" height="783" width="713" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> <b>(a)</b> On a prospective ECG-gated CT angiographic image obtained at 100 kVp in a patient with a BMI of 29 and a heart rate of 62 bpm, the left anterior descending artery is diffusely affected by noncalcified plaque. <b>(b)</b> On a retrospective ECG-gated CT angiographic image obtained at 100 kVp in a different patient with a BMI of 30 and a heart rate of 68 bpm, the right coronary artery is diffusely affected by noncalcified plaque. The extent and severity of coronary atherosclerotic disease are depicted with equal precision on the two images. DLPs of 92 mGy-cm <b>(a)</b> and 248 mGy-cm <b>(b)</b> were recorded.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig12b.jpeg" height="783" width="762" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> <b>(a)</b> On a prospective ECG-gated CT angiographic image obtained at 100 kVp in a patient with a BMI of 29 and a heart rate of 62 bpm, the left anterior descending artery is diffusely affected by noncalcified plaque. <b>(b)</b> On a retrospective ECG-gated CT angiographic image obtained at 100 kVp in a different patient with a BMI of 30 and a heart rate of 68 bpm, the right coronary artery is diffusely affected by noncalcified plaque. The extent and severity of coronary atherosclerotic disease are depicted with equal precision on the two images. DLPs of 92 mGy-cm <b>(a)</b> and 248 mGy-cm <b>(b)</b> were recorded.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig13a.jpeg" height="677" width="601" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> CT images of the pulmonary arteries (120 kVp, noise index = 16, CTDI<sub>vol</sub> = 288.6 mGy-cm, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained in a 72-year-old woman with a BMI of 32. The raw data were reconstructed with FBP <b>(a)</b>, a 30/70 blend of IR and FBP <b>(b)</b>, and a 50/50 blend of IR and FBP <b>(c)</b>. The image in <b>b</b> was subjectively graded as having the best quality (<a href="#r65" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r65">65</a>); the other two images demonstrated greater noise <b>(a)</b> and loss of detail <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig13b.jpeg" height="677" width="601" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> CT images of the pulmonary arteries (120 kVp, noise index = 16, CTDI<sub>vol</sub> = 288.6 mGy-cm, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained in a 72-year-old woman with a BMI of 32. The raw data were reconstructed with FBP <b>(a)</b>, a 30/70 blend of IR and FBP <b>(b)</b>, and a 50/50 blend of IR and FBP <b>(c)</b>. The image in <b>b</b> was subjectively graded as having the best quality (<a href="#r65" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r65">65</a>); the other two images demonstrated greater noise <b>(a)</b> and loss of detail <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.346140084/asset/images/large/rg.346140084.fig13c.jpeg" height="677" width="649" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> CT images of the pulmonary arteries (120 kVp, noise index = 16, CTDI<sub>vol</sub> = 288.6 mGy-cm, 2.5-mm section thickness) obtained in a 72-year-old woman with a BMI of 32. The raw data were reconstructed with FBP <b>(a)</b>, a 30/70 blend of IR and FBP <b>(b)</b>, and a 50/50 blend of IR and FBP <b>(c)</b>. The image in <b>b</b> was subjectively graded as having the best quality (<a href="#r65" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r65">65</a>); the other two images demonstrated greater noise <b>(a)</b> and loss of detail <b>(c)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.346140084&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Mettler FA Jr, Huda W, Yoshizumi TT, Mahesh M. Effective doses in radiology and diagnostic nuclear medicine: a catalog. <em>Radiology</em> 2008;248(1): 254–263.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiol.2481071451">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18566177/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Effective+doses+in+radiology+and+diagnostic+nuclear+medicine%3A+a+catalog&amp;author=FA+Mettler&amp;author=W+Huda&amp;author=TT+Yoshizumi&amp;author=M+Mahesh&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=Radiology&amp;pages=254-263&amp;doi=10.1148%2Fradiol.2481071451&amp;pmid=18566177">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-h